<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-576-368  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 576 368.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  August 28 1989 v6 n34 p28(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Much ado about very little. (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fegreus, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Product:   DEC VAX 9000 (Mainframe computer) (product development)IBM 3090 (Mainframe computer) (marketing)DEC VAX 6000-400 (Minicomputer) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Mainframe ComputersPerformanceProduct IntroductionMarket EntryMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Much Ado About Very LittleandM;Next month should mark the introduction of Aridus, the VAX 9000.andP;  But whileinvitations have yet to start arriving in the mail, some industry pundits arealready preparing to hold a wake for the first mainframe-class VAX.andO;Mainframe mavens are channeling their acerbic remarks toward Aridus'traditional VAX bus architecture for I/O, which is no match for IBM's I/Oarchitecture, they say.andP;  Aridus, they argue, will have a tough time competingwith IBM's 3090 series.andM;IBM's channel architecture has separate independent processors forinstructions and for I/O.andP;  (IBM's I/O processor is called a channel.)andP;  Thehost CPU initiates an I/O operation by writing a program that it deposits inmemory.andP;  The host then goes on to its next task while the channel handles theI/O.andM;The new VAX processors, however, don't suffer from the same I/O bottle-necksas VAX-11/780-class machines.andP;  In tests of the VAX 6000 Model 400's I/Osubsystem, DR Labs processed more than 600 QIOs per second using one HSC70and 29 RA90 disk drives.andP;  When testing halted abruptly because the RA90s ranout, the single Rigel CPU showed less than 5 percent utilization.andM;With enough disks, Rigel should probably deliver well in excess of 1,000 QIOsper second, if not several thousand.andP;  When a bottleneck does arise, itprobably will be in the computer interconnect (CI) port that attaches the VAX6000 to the CI's star coupler.andP;  And there's the rub.andP;  Aridus and Rigel willmost likely have identical I/O buses, peripherals, and hence, I/Operformance.andM;So the big question is: Why bother creating Aridus at all   A uniprandM;ocessor VAX offering 40 times the CPU power of a MicroVAX II is veryimpressive, but how often is that much concentrated power needed for asingle, sequential, commercial job?andP;  Multiple Rigel processors in a VAX 6000are already ideally suited for handling high-volume commercial-processingloads.andM;Sure, number-crunching applications in the high-end engineering andscientific markets are obvious targets for Aridus.andP;  With its vector-processoroption, Aridus looks like a good bet in this market in terms of performance.andO;But Aridus' ECL technology is quite expensive.andP;  And systems from Alliant andSilicon Graphics are already demonstrating that you don't need expensivevector processors if you can parallelize your code at the compile stage andexecute it simultaneously on several CPUs.andP;  DEC has been promising thiscapability on smaller, less expensive CPUs like Rigel since it introducedsymmetrical multiprocessing.andM;When all is said and done, it won't be surprising if Aridus' biggestcompetition comes from the VAX 6000 series, not the IBM 3090.andO;</TEXT></DOC>